<article about="/us/blog/threat-insight/operation-spoofedscholars-conversation-ta453" class="node--type--blog-post node--view-mode--full node node-blog-full _legacy_content _blog-full">
  



  <div class="breadcrumbs _legacy_element _breadcrumbs"><div class="nav-crumbs"><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog" class="breadcrum__item-link">Blog</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog/threat-insight" class="breadcrum__item-link">Threat Insight</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item">
            Operation SpoofedScholars: A Conversation with TA453          </div></div></div>

  <div class="blog-banner">

<h1 class="blog-banner__heading">
      <span>Operation SpoofedScholars: A Conversation with TA453</span>

  </h1>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="blog-content">
    <div class="blog-content__sharethis sharethis_toolbox sharethis_32x32_style">
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_label sharethis__label">Share with your network!</div>
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_buttons sharethis_buttons">
        <div class="sharethis-inline-share-buttons"></div>
        
<span class="addthis_button_subscribe at300b UNCONVERTED" title=Subscribe>
  <span class="at-icon-wrapper block-subscribe-button__trigger block-subscribe-button__addthis"></span>
</span>


      </div>
    </div>
        <div class="blog-content__metadata blog-content__metadata-author">
      <span class="blog-content__date">  <time datetime="2021-07-13T21:11:08Z">July 13, 2021</time>

</span>
        <span class="blog-content__author">
                Joshua Miller, Crista Giering, &amp; the Threat Research Team
  
        </span>
    </div>
    <div class="node-full__body blog-content__body">  <h3 paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{14}" paraid="1099737823">Key Takeaways&nbsp;</h3>

<ul>
	<li paraeid="{36e4941f-f9b1-4758-ad94-156a84eb42a7}{31}" paraid="1283724892"><a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/blog/threat-insight/badblood-ta453-targets-us-and-israeli-medical-research-personnel-credential" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">TA453</a>, an&nbsp;Iranian-state&nbsp;aligned actor,&nbsp;masqueraded as British scholars&nbsp;to covertly target individuals of intelligence interest to the Iranian government in what Proofpoint has dubbed Operation&nbsp;SpoofedScholars.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{36e4941f-f9b1-4758-ad94-156a84eb42a7}{49}" paraid="39497754">The email conversations were benign until TA453 provided a link to a compromised website hosting a credential harvesting page.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{36e4941f-f9b1-4758-ad94-156a84eb42a7}{54}" paraid="1814200167">The use of a legitimate but actor-compromised website is an increase in sophistication compared to TA453s historical Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures of using actor-controlled credential phishing websites.&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{36e4941f-f9b1-4758-ad94-156a84eb42a7}{61}" paraid="41846742">Proofpoint has worked with the appropriate authorities to conduct victim notification.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<h3 paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{59}" paraid="969181000">Overview&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{73}" paraid="1082547961">Masquerading as&nbsp;UK scholars&nbsp;with the University of Londons&nbsp;School of Oriental and African Studies&nbsp;(SOAS), the&nbsp;threat actor TA453 has been covertly approaching individuals&nbsp;since&nbsp;at least&nbsp;January 2021 to solicit sensitive information.&nbsp;The threat actor, an APT who we assess with high confidence supports Islamic&nbsp;Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) intelligence collection efforts,&nbsp;established backstopping for their credential phishing infrastructure by compromising a legitimate site of a highly regarded academic institution to deliver personalized credential harvesting pages disguised as registration links. Identified targets included experts in Middle Eastern affairs from think tanks, senior professors from well-known academic institutions, and journalists specializing in Middle Eastern coverage.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{105}" paraid="124091783">These connection attempts were detailed and extensive, often including lengthy conversations prior to presenting the next stage in the attack chain. Once the conversation was established, TA453 delivered a registration link to a legitimate but compromised website belonging to the University of Londons SOAS radio. The&nbsp;compromised site&nbsp;was configured to capture a variety of credentials. Of note, TA453 also targeted the personal email accounts of at least one of their targets.&nbsp;In subsequent phishing&nbsp;emails, TA453&nbsp;shifted their tactics and&nbsp;began delivering the registration link earlier&nbsp;in their engagement with the target&nbsp;without requiring extensive conversation.&nbsp;This operation, dubbed&nbsp;SpoofedScholars,&nbsp;represents one of the more sophisticated TA453 campaigns&nbsp;identified&nbsp;by&nbsp;Proofpoint.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{149}" paraid="746131951"><img alt="Text Box" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{152}" paraid="585384165">Chatting with TA453&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{162}" paraid="149837941">In early 2021, a TA453 persona,&nbsp;Dr.Hanns&nbsp;Bjoern&nbsp;Kendel, Senior Teaching and Research Fellow at SOAS University in London,&nbsp;used email address&nbsp;hannse.kendel4[@]gmail.com&nbsp;to solicit conversations&nbsp;with targets.&nbsp;The following is&nbsp;a brief summary&nbsp;of&nbsp;an&nbsp;example conversation&nbsp;observed&nbsp;by Proofpoint Threat Research:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{222}" paraid="1137408247">TA453&nbsp;sent an initial email&nbsp;trying to entice the target with a prospective invitation to an online conference on The US Security Challenges in the Middle East. TA453 strived to connect with the&nbsp;individual&nbsp;via phone to discuss the invitation; however, after the target hedged&nbsp;and emphatically stated that they wanted a written proposal with the details, TA453 acquiesced with conference specifics. After a little back and forth that verified the targets interest, TA453&nbsp;provided a detailed invitation to the fake conference (Figure 1). The conversation concluded with TA453 attempting to get the target to connect via&nbsp;videoconferencing.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{910e4aab-644f-4c1f-8e65-b0074b36d3d0}{252}" paraid="516752180"><img alt="Text, letter

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{2}" paraid="2076615315"><em>Figure 1. Fake conference invitation.&nbsp;</em></p>

<h3 paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{8}" paraid="729564706">Conversation Analysis&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{20}" paraid="1172138616">Throughout the conversation, Proofpoint identified a few interesting themes:&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{26}" paraid="1514818110">TA453 demonstrates passable English skills and is open to voice communication via videoconferencing.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{33}" paraid="1891822638">TA453 demonstrates an interest in mobile phone numbers, possibly for mobile malware or additional phishing.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{40}" paraid="771065128">TA453 repeatedly demonstrated a desire to connect with the target in real-time.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<h3 paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{49}" paraid="1758528578">Personal Targeting&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{55}" paraid="899497748">In addition to&nbsp;Hanns solicitations, at least one target received a credential harvesting email to their personal email account. This attempt did not masquerade as Dr.&nbsp;Kendel&nbsp;but did still attempt to harvest credentials from the target.&nbsp;Currently, Proofpoint does not have more information on this specific kill chain.&nbsp;</p>

<h3 aria-level="1" paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{77}" paraid="391275614" role="heading">Campaign&nbsp;Breakdown&nbsp;</h3>

<p aria-level="1" paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{85}" paraid="854779380" role="heading"><strong>Targets</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{91}" paraid="84067524">TA453 targets in&nbsp;Operation&nbsp;SpoofedScholars&nbsp;can be clustered into three main categories that are consistent with the IRGCs historical collection priorities.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{103}" paraid="1447244709">Senior think tank personnel&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{110}" paraid="1797338043">Journalists focused on Middle Eastern affairs&nbsp;</li>
	<li paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{117}" paraid="1942647106">Professors&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{128}" paraid="1305038380">These groupings consistently have information of interest to the Iranian government, including, but not limited to, information about foreign policy, insights into Iranian dissident movements, and understanding of U.S. nuclear negotiations, and most of the identified targets have been previously targeted by TA453.&nbsp;Targeting appeared to be highly selective,&nbsp;with less than ten organizations targeted, according to Proofpoint data.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{152}" paraid="741560523"><strong>Infrastructure</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{158}" paraid="1244747974">Once TA453 established a time for the target to activate their invitation, the&nbsp;TA453&nbsp;persona&nbsp;provided the personalized link to&nbsp;the&nbsp;intended victim.&nbsp;The link led to a Webinar Control Panel on a legitimate&nbsp;but compromised&nbsp;website&nbsp;belonging to University of Londons SOAS, a research institution.&nbsp;According to Proofpoint research, while TA453 does appear to have elevated privileges allowing them to create credential harvesting pages at&nbsp;soasradio[.]org, other pages on the site continue to host legitimate SOAS-affiliated content.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{f55cf113-2184-421e-95a1-ec427f9e6d08}{208}" paraid="811154381">TA453 strengthened the credibility of the attempted credential harvest by&nbsp;utilizing&nbsp;personas&nbsp;masquerading as legitimate affiliates&nbsp;of SOAS&nbsp;to deliver the malicious links. The displayed webpage (Figure&nbsp;2) offers users the ability to use OpenID to log in with the following mail providers; Google, Yahoo, Microsoft, iCloud, Outlook, AOL, mail.ru, Email, and Facebook.&nbsp;The website URI&nbsp;was&nbsp;hxxps://soasradio[.]org/connect/?memberemailid=&nbsp;[RedactedInitials&nbsp;of Target]-[String of alphanumeric characters].&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{21}" paraid="2038108303"><img alt="Graphical user interface

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{26}" paraid="1888778642"><em>Figure&nbsp;2. SOAS displayed webpage.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{42}" paraid="1338818592">When a particular provider is clicked, a pop-up box&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;3)&nbsp;displays the actual credential phishing box. Of the options, Google, Microsoft, and&nbsp;Email buttons prefilled the targets email address. Based on the variety of email providers along with TA453s insistence that the target log on when TA453 was online, Proofpoint assesses that TA453 was planning on immediately validating the captured credentials manually.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{60}" paraid="559746646"><img alt="microsoft " data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="01e41433-ad9d-413b-af1f-c80ddc8a638e" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/MicrosoftTeams-image%20%287%29.png" width="1280" height="1246" loading="lazy"></p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{63}" paraid="167489080"><em>Figure&nbsp;3.&nbsp;AOL&nbsp;login&nbsp;window&nbsp;&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{63}" paraid="167489080">Hanns&nbsp;Kendel&nbsp;was not the only SOAS scholar spoofed by TA453&nbsp;during&nbsp;Operation&nbsp;SpoofedScholars.&nbsp;Months later,&nbsp;TA453 began spoofing&nbsp;Tolga&nbsp;Sinmazdemir, another&nbsp;individual associated with&nbsp;SOAS.&nbsp;These&nbsp;emails&nbsp;solicited contributions to a&nbsp;DIPS Conference&nbsp;and would have likely followed a similar kill chain&nbsp;discussed above. In mid-May,&nbsp;TA453&nbsp;returned, using a different&nbsp;email&nbsp;(hanse.kendel4[@]gmail.com)&nbsp;to recruit for a webinar.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{163}" paraid="1302381144"><strong>Attribution</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{171}" paraid="1135956274">As discussed previously in Proofpoints research on TA453s&nbsp;<a data-entity-substitution="canonical" data-entity-type="node" data-entity-uuid="2a23ca91-31e9-4342-9ff1-09da104f6585" href="/us/blog/threat-insight/badblood-ta453-targets-us-and-israeli-medical-research-personnel-credential" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank" title="BadBlood: TA453 Targets US and Israeli Medical Research Personnel in Credential Phishing Campaigns ">BadBlood</a>&nbsp;campaign, Proofpoint analysts cannot independently confirm that TA453 is part of the IRGC.&nbsp;However, the tactics and techniques used by the group and their overall targeting detected by Proofpoint is in line with IRGC intelligence collection priorities, which gives us high confidence in our assessment that&nbsp;TA453 operates in&nbsp;support&nbsp;of&nbsp;the IRGC.&nbsp;The IRGC, specifically the IRGC Intelligence Organization, collects intelligence and conducts operations in support of a variety of assigned responsibilities. According to the Meir Amit Intelligence and Terrorism Information Centers November 2020&nbsp;<a href="https://www.terrorism-info.org.il/en/the-intelligence-organization-of-the-irgc-a-major-iranian-intelligence-apparatus/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">report</a>, some of the IRGC IOs responsibilities include foiling political subversion, combating western cultural penetration, and supporting the arrest of Iranian dual nationals.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{211}" paraid="1769792031">Likewise, attribution specifically for&nbsp;Operation&nbsp;SpoofedScholars&nbsp;is based on TTP similarities to previous TA453 campaigns and consistency with TA453s historical targeting. TA453 often uses free email providers to spoof individuals familiar to their targets to increase the likelihood of successful compromise. Additionally, as previously discussed, TA453 concentrates their credential phishing to specific individuals of interest&nbsp;to&nbsp;collect&nbsp;intelligence through exfiltration of sensitive email and contacts or initial access for future phishing campaigns.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{233}" paraid="1255887870"><strong>Mitigation</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{251}" paraid="1076835760">For specific mitigations against Operation&nbsp;SpoofedScholars, Proofpoint recommends&nbsp;investigating network traffic to&nbsp;soasradio[.]org,&nbsp;specifically&nbsp;URIs starting with&nbsp;hxxps://soasradio[.]org/connect/?memberemailid=.&nbsp;Additionally, emails from&nbsp;hanse.kendel4[@]gmail.com,&nbsp;hannse.kendel4[@]gmail.com,&nbsp;and&nbsp;&nbsp;t.sinmazdemir32[@]gmail.com&nbsp;should be considered suspect and investigated.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{70bfd6b3-f1a9-4c09-9649-c44a75d61b72}{251}" paraid="1076835760">Broader mitigation efforts against TA453 campaigns include increased awareness and investigation of unusual communication from professional contacts. Academics, journalists, and think tank&nbsp;scholars&nbsp;should&nbsp;practice caution and verify the identity of the individuals offering them unique opportunities, especially if those opportunities occur virtually. Using multifactor authentication&nbsp;provides another layer of protection against TA453 credential harvesting.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<h3 paraeid="{8469f035-5e2f-4ba1-a1b0-cb99590133e5}{64}" paraid="392034996"><strong>Conclusion</strong>&nbsp;</h3>

<p paraeid="{8469f035-5e2f-4ba1-a1b0-cb99590133e5}{74}" paraid="154368545">TA453&nbsp;illegally obtained access to a website belonging to a world class academic institution&nbsp;to&nbsp;leverage the&nbsp;compromised infrastructure to harvest the credentials of their intended targets.&nbsp;The use of legitimate,&nbsp;but compromised,&nbsp;infrastructure represents an increase in TA453s sophistication&nbsp;and will almost certainly&nbsp;be reflected in future campaigns. TA453 continues to&nbsp;iterate,&nbsp;innovate,&nbsp;and collect&nbsp;in support of IRGC collection priorities. While&nbsp;some&nbsp;of the identified selectors&nbsp;no longer appear to be active in TA453 operations, Proofpoint assesses with high confidence that TA453 will continue&nbsp;to&nbsp;spoof scholars&nbsp;around the world&nbsp;in support of&nbsp;TA453s intelligence collection&nbsp;operations&nbsp;in&nbsp;support of Iranian government interests.&nbsp;Academics, journalists, and think tank personnel&nbsp;should practice caution and verify the&nbsp;identity of the individuals offering them unique opportunities.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{8469f035-5e2f-4ba1-a1b0-cb99590133e5}{152}" paraid="2055335020"><strong>ET</strong> <strong>Signature</strong>&nbsp;</p>
